# gen117 (rung 19, deeper): the OBSERVATION-DRIVEN branching act-loop. In gen116
# the agent's action was a fixed operation; here the action each step is CHOSEN
# by observing the state. A two-branch rule ("if it is even, halve it; if it is
# odd, triple it and add 1") is parsed into per-branch operation sequences, and
# the loop applies the branch that the current value's parity selects — until the
# goal is reached. This is the Collatz process: its step count is famously
# unpredictable, so the answer can ONLY come from running the loop, never a
# formula. parrot0 has no model inside — it reads the rule and iterates it.

# Collatz from 27 takes 111 steps. A long trajectory is shown head ... tail.
> start at 27. if it is even, halve it. if it is odd, triple it and add 1. repeat until it reaches 1.
< Reached 1 after 111 steps: 27 -> 82 -> 41 -> 124 -> 62 -> 31 -> 94 -> 47 -> 142 -> ... -> 1.

# The proof trace is the real loop — 111 OBSERVED steps, not a stored answer.
> how do you know?
< Because branching act-loop: 111 observed steps, 27 -> 82 -> 41 -> 124 -> 62 -> 31 -> 94 -> 47 -> 142 -> ... -> 1.

# Held-out start (6): a different, fully-shown trajectory of 8 steps — the count
# is produced by iterating the same rule, never memorized.
> start at 6. if it is even, halve it. if it is odd, triple it and add 1. repeat until it reaches 1.
< Reached 1 after 8 steps: 6 -> 3 -> 10 -> 5 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1.